    "---\n",
    "## 9. Summary & Discussion\n",
    "\n",
    "### What we built\n",
    "| Component | Choice | Rationale |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Molecular representation | Morgan fingerprints (2048 bits, r=2) + 21 physicochemical descriptors | Captures both local substructure and global molecular properties |\n",
    "| Baseline | Random Forest | Robust, handles sparse features, no scaling needed |\n",
    "| Extended | XGBoost | Gradient boosting often stronger on tabular data |\n",
    "| Final | Tuned ensemble (RF + XGB) | Averaging diverse models reduces variance |\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key findings\n",
    "- **Molecular weight, logP, TPSA** are among the most informative descriptors — consistent with known toxicokinetics (absorption, distribution, metabolism depend on these)\n",
    "- **Highly toxic compounds** (log LD50 < 1.5) are hardest to predict, likely due to class imbalance\n",
    "- The model generalizes well (train–test R² gap is small), suggesting limited overfitting\n",
    "\n",
    "### Limitations\n",
    "- 2D fingerprints don't capture 3D conformation (stereochemistry may matter)\n",
    "- LD50 is a blunt measure of toxicity — mechanism of action is ignored\n",
    "- Some chemical classes may be underrepresented in the training data\n",
    "- Rat oral LD50 may not generalize perfectly to human toxicity\n",
    "\n",
    "### Potential improvements (if more time)\n",
    "- Graph Neural Networks (GNN) operating directly on molecular graphs\n",
    "- Scaffold-based cross-validation (stricter generalization test)\n",
    "- SHAP values for per-prediction explanations\n",
    "- Uncertainty quantification (confidence intervals per prediction)"
   ]
  }
